Sprint 3 Development:¶

Project: Crop Yield Prediction using ML¶

1. A brief introduction to the problem¶

Crop Yield Prediction Dataset

Predicting crop yield of 10 most consumed crops in 🌏

The Crop Yield Prediction project aims to predict the yield of different crops based on various environmental and agricultural factors. This project is crucial for agricultural planning, resource allocation, and ensuring food security. Accurate predictions can help farmers and policymakers make informed decisions about crop management, irrigation, and pest control strategies.

The dataset contains historical data on crop yield from year 1990 to 2013 along with several features such as:

  1. Area: The geographical area (country) where the crop is grown.

  2. Year: The year of the recorded data.

  3. Crop_Name: The name of the crop.

  4. yield_in_hg/ha: The yield of the crop in hectograms per hectare.

  5. total_pesticides_in_tonnes: The total amount of pesticides used in tonnes.

  6. average_rain_fall_mm_per_year: The average annual rainfall in millimeters.

  7. avg_temp: The average temperature in degrees Celsius.

  8. Area Code: The code representing the geographical area.

  9. Item Code: The code representing the crop.

On Kaggle at Crop Yield Prediction Dataset, there are 33 codes, and two caught our attention because of their organization and the good results they exposed:

https://www.kaggle.com/code/patelris/crop-yield-eda-viz

https://www.kaggle.com/code/mahmoudmagdyelnahal/crop-yield-prediction-99

5.3. Generate new features to facilitate prediction.¶

In [37]:
# rain_avg_temp - capture the combined effect of  two environmental factors avg_temp and average_rain_fall_mm_per_year on crop yield
df_crop_yield['rain_avg_temp']= df_crop_yield['avg_temp'] * df_crop_yield['average_rain_fall_mm_per_year']


# pesticide_avg_rain - provides a measure of pesticide usage relative to rainfall
df_crop_yield['pesticide_avg_rain']= np.log(df_crop_yield['total_pesticides_in_tonnes'] / df_crop_yield['average_rain_fall_mm_per_year'])


# pesticide_avg_temp - provides a measure of pesticide usage relative to temperature
df_crop_yield['pesticide_avg_temp']= np.log(df_crop_yield['total_pesticides_in_tonnes'] / df_crop_yield['avg_temp'])

# pesticide_temp_rain- combines the effects of temperature and rainfall on pesticide usage
df_crop_yield['pesticide_temp_rain']= (df_crop_yield['pesticide_avg_temp'] / df_crop_yield['pesticide_avg_rain'])

# avg_rain_log - help normalize the data and reduce the effect of extreme values
df_crop_yield['avg_rain_log'] = np.log(df_crop_yield['average_rain_fall_mm_per_year'])

# avg_temp_rain_log - capture the relative effect of temperature adjusted by the log of rainfall
df_crop_yield['avg_temp_rain_log']=df_crop_yield['avg_temp'] /  df_crop_yield['avg_rain_log']

    ('Random Forest', RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)),
    ('Gradient Boost', GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=100, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=3, random_state=42)),
    ('XGBoost', XGBRegressor(random_state=42)),
    ('KNN', KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=5)),
    ('Decision Tree', DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42)),
    ('Bagging Regressor', BaggingRegressor(n_estimators=150, random_state=42))
]

colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c', '#d62728', '#9467bd', '#8c564b', '#e377c2']

for i, (name, model) in enumerate(models):
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    r2 = model.score(X_test, y_test)  # R-squared value
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    results.append((name, r2, mse))
    
    acc_train = model.score(X_train, y_train) * 100
    acc_test = model.score(X_test, y_test) * 100
    print(f'The R-squared of the {name} Model Train is {acc_train:.2f}')
    print(f'The R-squared of the {name} Model Test is {acc_test:.2f}')
    
    plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred, s=10, color=colors[i % len(colors)])
    plt.xlabel('Actual Values')
    plt.ylabel('Predicted Values')
    plt.plot([min(y_test), max(y_test)], [min(y_test), max(y_test)], color='green', linewidth=4)
    plt.title(f'{name} Evaluation')
    plt.show()
